00:21:23,496 --> 00:21:26,248
They were from the Pas de Calais.

254
00:21:26,291 --> 00:21:28,912
Bredoteau. What more can I say?

255
00:22:33,775 --> 00:22:37,357
Groping under the photo booth
is Nino Quincampoix.

256
00:22:41,824 --> 00:22:46,487
When Amélie lacked playmates,
Nino had too many.

257
00:22:57,632 --> 00:23:02,709
Five miles apart, one dreamed
of having a sister, the other a brother

258
00:23:02,762 --> 00:23:04,801
to spend all their time with.

259
00:23:26,452 --> 00:23:27,483
Hi, Dad.

260
00:23:29,122 --> 00:23:30,498
A new friend?

261
00:23:31,541 --> 00:23:33,748
No, I've had him for years.

262
00:23:33,793 --> 00:23:37,708
Your mother hated him,
so he lived in the tool shed.

263
00:23:37,756 --> 00:23:40,756
There. Let's reconcile them.

264
00:23:44,178 --> 00:23:46,254
There. Not bad, eh?

265
00:23:50,142 --> 00:23:55,600
Dad, if you found a precious relic
from your childhood,

266
00:23:55,649 --> 00:23:59,516
how would it make you feel?
Happy? Sad? Nostalgic? What?

267
00:24:00,612 --> 00:24:03,103
I didn't have this gnome when I was a child.

268
00:24:03,156 --> 00:24:06,774
He was a retirement gift from my old regiment.

269
00:24:06,826 --> 00:24:11,287
No, I mean something you hid
like a secret treasure.

270
00:24:12,832 --> 00:24:14,909
I should varnish him before autumn.

271
00:24:18,839 --> 00:24:21,460
I'll make some tea. Do you want some?

272
00:24:21,508 --> 00:24:23,584
Breathe in. Hold still.

273
00:24:25,678 --> 00:24:27,386
Better now?

274
00:24:27,430 --> 00:24:29,304
Shut the door!

275
00:24:29,349 --> 00:24:31,388
There's a howling gale.

276
00:24:31,434 --> 00:24:33,426
It's hardly Siberia.

277
00:24:33,478 --> 00:24:36,052
I can see you're not allergic

278
00:24:36,106 --> 00:24:40,768
to car fumes.
I almost coughed up my pleura last night.

279
00:24:40,819 --> 00:24:42,313
Coughed up a pleura? Sure.

280
00:24:42,362 --> 00:24:45,945
- What's on the menu today, Suzanne?
- Endives au gratin.

281
00:24:45,991 --> 00:24:48,446
They'll have you on your knees, you'll see.

282
00:24:48,493 --> 00:24:49,691
They're good, then?

283
00:24:49,744 --> 00:24:51,950
- Depends where.
- If it's at the toilet...

284
00:24:51,996 --> 00:24:53,277
Not good!

285
00:24:58,837 --> 00:25:02,787
12:15, laughs orgasmically
to attract alpha male.

286
00:25:02,841 --> 00:25:05,758
He's going to drive me berserk!

287
00:25:05,802 --> 00:25:09,551
Can't he give up?
There are plenty of other bars.

288
00:25:09,597 --> 00:25:11,555
Goodbye.

289
00:25:11,599 --> 00:25:12,844
Suzanne.

290
00:25:12,892 --> 00:25:14,801
- Suzanne.
- Yes.

291
00:25:14,852 --> 00:25:17,604
"Au gratin" means white sauce, right?

292
00:25:17,647 --> 00:25:19,271
Yes, why?

293
00:25:19,315 --> 00:25:24,357
I can't stomach it. Like you and horse meat.

294
00:25:24,404 --> 00:25:27,156
It's not my stomach, it's my memory.

295
00:25:28,200 --> 00:25:29,991
I'd rather cook human flesh.

296
00:25:30,035 --> 00:25:32,074
You're kidding!

297
00:25:43,214 --> 00:25:47,592
Suzanne, would you mind if I left early today?

298
00:25:47,636 --> 00:25:49,675
What's his name?

299
00:25:49,721 --> 00:25:51,797
Dominique Bredoteau.

300
00:25:57,353 --> 00:25:59,180
Hello.

301
00:26:00,315 --> 00:26:02,224
Are you Dominique Bredoteau?

302
00:26:02,275 --> 00:26:03,650
That's me.

303
00:26:03,693 --> 00:26:05,685
Why?

304
00:26:05,736 --> 00:26:07,813
It's about...

305
00:26:08,866 --> 00:26:10,110
...the petition.

306
00:26:10,158 --> 00:26:11,569
Petition?

307
00:26:11,618 --> 00:26:16,363
Yes. The petition to...

308
00:26:17,791 --> 00:26:19,700
...to canonise Lady Di.

309
00:26:19,751 --> 00:26:21,411
No, thanks.

310
00:26:21,461 --> 00:26:22,492
No.

311
00:26:30,304 --> 00:26:32,877
Ladies and gentlemen, sorry to bother you...

312
00:26:37,853 --> 00:26:40,011
- Yes?
- Hello.

313
00:26:40,063 --> 00:26:43,728
I'm looking for Dominique Bredoteau
for the European census.

314
00:26:44,901 --> 00:26:46,940
Come up. Third floor.

315
00:26:57,289 --> 00:26:58,320
Hello, kitten.

316
00:27:01,710 --> 00:27:02,908
Earl Grey?

317
00:27:02,961 --> 00:27:05,037
Jasmine?

318
00:27:05,088 --> 00:27:08,124
What will you have?

319
00:27:12,011 --> 00:27:13,471
I'm working.

320
00:27:22,272 --> 00:27:25,143
There. I'm coming.

321
00:27:25,192 --> 00:27:29,569
Do you know where I can find
Dominique Bredoteau?

322
00:27:29,612 --> 00:27:31,901
Oh, my poor dear!

323
00:27:32,991 --> 00:27:34,153
You just missed him.

324
00:27:35,201 --> 00:27:37,954
Look, there he goes now.

325
00:27:47,422 --> 00:27:48,453
Bre-to-deau.

326
00:27:49,966 --> 00:27:51,377
Not Bre-do-teau.

327
00:27:51,426 --> 00:27:53,300
You need

328
00:27:53,344 --> 00:27:56,844
a glass of mulled wine.

329
00:27:56,889 --> 00:27:58,717
Come in.

330
00:27:58,767 --> 00:28:00,012
Come on in.

331
00:28:03,021 --> 00:28:07,648
I've lived here for five years.
This is the first time we've met.

332
00:28:07,693 --> 00:28:10,480
I never go out on the landing.

333
00:28:10,529 --> 00:28:14,526
I'm fussy about who I meet.

334
00:28:14,574 --> 00:28:16,152
They're all creeps anyway.

335
00:28:18,369 --> 00:28:20,944
Come in. Here.

336
00:28:20,998 --> 00:28:22,373
Come in.

337
00:28:23,417 --> 00:28:25,990
They call me the Glass Man,

338
00:28:26,044 --> 00:28:29,627
but my name is Raymond Dufayel.

339
00:28:30,757 --> 00:28:35,051
- Amélie Poulain. I'm a waitress at...
- The Two Windmills. I know.

340
00:28:36,096 --> 00:28:41,220
And you've come back empty-handed
from your search for Bretodeau.

341
00:28:42,727 --> 00:28:45,978
Because it's not "do", it's "to".

342
00:28:46,023 --> 00:28:48,561
- Like "Toto".
- Thank you.

343
00:28:52,362 --> 00:28:54,070
I love that painting.

344
00:28:54,114 --> 00:28:56,819
It's the Luncheon Of The Boating Party.

345
00:28:58,535 --> 00:28:59,566
By Renoir.

346
00:29:05,417 --> 00:29:09,367
I've painted one each year for twenty years.

347
00:29:11,006 --> 00:29:13,711
The hardest part is the looks.

348
00:29:13,759 --> 00:29:19,844
I sometimes feel they deliberately change
their mood as soon as my back's turned.

349
00:29:19,890 --> 00:29:21,549
They look quite happy there.

350
00:29:21,600 --> 00:29:23,888
They should be.

351
00:29:23,935 --> 00:29:26,011
This year they had hare with morels.

352
00:29:27,230 --> 00:29:30,849
And waffles with jam for the children.

353
00:29:30,901 --> 00:29:36,405
Now, what have I done
with that piece of paper?

354
00:29:38,533 --> 00:29:43,907
Ah, you've noticed my video camera
at the window.

355
00:29:43,955 --> 00:29:46,624
It's a gift from my sister-in-law.

356
00:29:46,666 --> 00:29:49,537
I put it there

357
00:29:49,586 --> 00:29:52,504
so I don't need to wind up my clocks.

358
00:29:53,924 --> 00:29:56,545
After all these years,

359
00:29:56,593 --> 00:30:00,922
the only person I still can't capture

360
00:30:00,973 --> 00:30:03,261
is the girl with the glass of water.

361
00:30:03,308 --> 00:30:04,802
She's in the middle,

362
00:30:04,851 --> 00:30:07,686
yet she's on the outside.

363
00:30:09,314 --> 00:30:11,887
Maybe she's just different from the others.

364
00:30:13,277 --> 00:30:14,736
In what way?

365
00:30:16,405 --> 00:30:17,816
I don't know.

366
00:30:17,865 --> 00:30:23,107
When she was little, she can't
have played much with other children.

367
00:30:24,913 --> 00:30:27,202
Maybe never.

368
00:30:30,919 --> 00:30:32,294
Here.

369
00:30:32,337 --> 00:30:36,287
Dominique Bretodeau, 27 Rue Mouffetard.

370
00:30:37,593 --> 00:30:38,873
It's for you.

371
00:30:40,095 --> 00:30:45,090
Every Tuesday morning,
Dominique Bretodeau goes to buy a chicken.

372
00:30:45,142 --> 00:30:48,261
He usually roasts it
and has it with sauté potatoes.

373
00:30:48,311 --> 00:30:51,597
After carving the legs,
the breast and the wings,

374
00:30:51,648 --> 00:30:55,692
he loves picking the hot carcass
with his fingers,

375
00:30:55,735 --> 00:30:57,395
starting with the oysters.

376
00:31:00,574 --> 00:31:04,406
But not today. Bretodeau won't buy a chicken.

377
00:31:04,453 --> 00:31:05,912
He'll go no further

378
00:31:05,954 --> 00:31:07,614
than this phone booth here.

379
00:32:17,985 --> 00:32:21,318
In a flash, it all came back to him.

380
00:32:21,363 --> 00:32:24,566
Federico Bahamontes
winning the Tour de France in '59.

381
00:32:27,578 --> 00:32:29,654
Aunt Josette's slips.

382
00:32:32,208 --> 00:32:35,292
And most of all, that tragic day.

383
00:32:36,670 --> 00:32:40,288
That tragic day
when he won all the marbles at break time.

384
00:32:49,140 --> 00:32:50,173
Bretodeau!

385
00:32:53,354 --> 00:32:54,516
Bretodeau!

386
00:33:01,904 --> 00:33:04,276
The pinch, Bretodeau!

387
00:33:04,323 --> 00:33:06,399
Do you understand, Bretodeau?

388
00:33:14,125 --> 00:33:15,500
Cognac, please.

389
00:33:20,881 --> 00:33:23,586
It's amazing, what just happened to me.

390
00:33:23,634 --> 00:33:27,845
It must be my guardian angel.
It's the only explanation.

391
00:33:27,888 --> 00:33:30,343
It was as if the phone booth was calling me.

392
00:33:30,390 --> 00:33:32,798
It rang and rang.

393
00:33:35,313 --> 00:33:38,397
Same here. The microwave's calling me.

394
00:33:40,651 --> 00:33:42,727
I'll have another cognac.

395
00:33:51,411 --> 00:33:52,870
Life's strange.

396
00:33:55,373 --> 00:33:59,787
To a kid, time always drags.
Suddenly you're 50.

397
00:34:01,964 --> 00:34:04,040
All that's left of your childhood

398
00:34:04,091 --> 00:34:06,333
fits in a little box,

399
00:34:06,385 --> 00:34:07,844
a little rusty box.

400
00:34:11,265 --> 00:34:13,802
Have you got kids, miss?

401
00:34:18,939 --> 00:34:21,561
I have a daughter.
She must be about your age.

402
00:34:25,321 --> 00:34:27,313
We haven't spoken for years.

403
00:34:28,365 --> 00:34:31,319
I heard she had a child, a boy.

404
00:34:32,494 --> 00:34:33,525
His name is Lucas.

405
00:34:40,127 --> 00:34:44,670
I think it's time I looked them up
before I'm in a box myself.

406
00:34:45,966 --> 00:34:47,425
Don't you think?

407
00:34:55,017 --> 00:34:59,394
Amélie suddenly has a strange feeling
of complete harmony.

408
00:34:59,438 --> 00:35:05,393
It's a perfect moment. Soft light,
a scent in the air, the quiet murmur of the city,

409
00:35:06,737 --> 00:35:09,940
She breathes deeply.
Life seems so simple and clear.

410
00:35:09,990 --> 00:35:14,783
A surge of love,
an urge to help mankind suddenly engulfs her.

411
00:35:27,175 --> 00:35:29,796
Let me help you. Step down.

412
00:35:29,844 --> 00:35:32,880
Off we go!
We just passed the drum major's widow!

413
00:35:32,930 --> 00:35:35,931
She's worn his coat since the day he died.
Careful.

414
00:35:35,975 --> 00:35:39,094
The horse's head on the butcher's
has lost an ear.

415
00:35:39,144 --> 00:35:42,679
That's the florist laughing. He has crinkly eyes.

416
00:35:42,731 --> 00:35:45,815
In the bakery window there are lollipops!

417
00:35:45,859 --> 00:35:47,650
Mmm. Smell that.

418
00:35:47,694 --> 00:35:49,937
They're giving out melon slices.

419
00:35:51,616 --> 00:35:54,071
Sugarplum ice cream!

420
00:35:54,118 --> 00:35:56,787
We're passing the pork butcher.

421
00:35:56,829 --> 00:35:59,236
Ham, 79 francs. Spareribs, 45!

422
00:35:59,290 --> 00:36:04,117
Now the cheese shop.
Picodons are 12.90, cabecous 23.50.

423
00:36:04,169 --> 00:36:08,748
At the butcher's a baby's watching a dog
that's watching the chickens roasting.

424
00:36:08,799 --> 00:36:12,216
Now we're at the newspaper kiosk
by the métro.

425
00:36:12,261 --> 00:36:14,337
I'll leave you here. Bye.

426
00:37:05,815 --> 00:37:08,103
"She can't relate to other people."

427
00:37:10,319 --> 00:37:13,189
"She was always a lonely child."

428
00:37:16,158 --> 00:37:19,112
On a sparkling evening in July,

429
00:37:19,161 --> 00:37:22,032
while on the beaches holidaymakers

430
00:37:22,081 --> 00:37:24,654
relax in the new-found sun,

431
00:37:24,709 --> 00:37:27,247
and in Paris the sweltering crowds

432
00:37:27,294 --> 00:37:29,667
gaze at the first bursts

433
00:37:29,713 --> 00:37:32,383
of the traditional fireworks,
Amélie Poulain,

434
00:37:32,424 --> 00:37:36,173
godmother of outcasts,

435
00:37:36,220 --> 00:37:38,711
Madonna of the unloved,

436
00:37:38,764 --> 00:37:40,922
finally succumbs to exhaustion.

437
00:37:40,974 --> 00:37:45,720
In Paris' grief-stricken streets,

438
00:37:45,771 --> 00:37:48,606
a vast throng of mourners

439
00:37:48,649 --> 00:37:51,769
line her funeral route in silence

440
00:37:51,819 --> 00:37:56,279
with the measureless sorrow
of newly orphaned children.

441
00:37:57,324 --> 00:37:59,447
What a strange destiny for one

442
00:37:59,493 --> 00:38:00,904
who gave her all,

443
00:38:00,953 --> 00:38:06,624
yet took such joy in life's simple pleasures.

444
00:38:06,667 --> 00:38:10,286
Like Don Quixote, she pitted herself

445
00:38:10,338 --> 00:38:13,504
against the grinding windmill
of all life's miseries.

446
00:38:25,936 --> 00:38:28,013
It was a losing battle

447
00:38:28,064 --> 00:38:30,056
that claimed her life too soon.

448
00:38:30,108 --> 00:38:32,396
At barely 23, Amélie Poulain

449
00:38:32,443 --> 00:38:36,061
let her young, tired body merge

450
00:38:36,113 --> 00:38:39,529
with the ebb and flow of universal woe.

451
00:38:39,575 --> 00:38:45,827
As she went, she felt a stab of regret
for letting her father die

452
00:38:45,873 --> 00:38:49,456
without trying to give his stifled life

453
00:38:49,502 --> 00:38:53,749
the breath of air she had given

454
00:38:53,798 --> 00:38:55,874
to so many others.

455
00:41:12,145 --> 00:41:13,176
Wait!

456
00:41:18,234 --> 00:41:20,025
Wait!

457
00:41:22,905 --> 00:41:23,936
Wait...

458
00:41:25,324 --> 00:41:26,356
Wait, wait!

459
00:42:12,914 --> 00:42:18,335
Pages full of dud ID photos
torn up and discarded by their owners,

460
00:42:18,378 --> 00:42:22,043
carefully reassembled by some oddball.

461
00:42:23,090 --> 00:42:25,166
Some family album!

462
00:42:29,305 --> 00:42:30,929
A pack of Gauloises.

463
00:42:30,973 --> 00:42:35,054
Just a second. It's so smoky in here.
Can you tell me where they are?

464
00:42:35,103 --> 00:42:37,772
- I can't see a thing.
- More to the left.

465
00:42:37,814 --> 00:42:39,474
- There?
- A bit more. There.

466
00:42:42,318 --> 00:42:44,643
Thank you. You need change.

467
00:42:44,695 --> 00:42:47,103
Forget it.

468
00:42:47,156 --> 00:42:49,149
- Yes?
- A mauresque.

469
00:42:49,200 --> 00:42:51,691
A mauresque for the young man.

470
00:42:51,744 --> 00:42:55,160
One kir aligoté, one mauresque,
and two mint sodas.

471
00:42:55,205 --> 00:42:58,492
Was that prenuptial or post-coital smooching?

472
00:42:58,543 --> 00:43:00,619
Is your bullshit congenital?

473
00:43:02,630 --> 00:43:04,706
- Prenuptial.
- Don't worry.

474
00:43:04,757 --> 00:43:06,833
You'll find Mr. Right one day.

475
00:43:07,969 --> 00:43:11,254
All women want to sleep on a man's shoulder.
All of them.

476
00:43:11,305 --> 00:43:16,133
All men snore after a few drinks,
and I have a musical ear.

477
00:43:16,185 --> 00:43:19,934
I had an operation on my nasal cavities.

478
00:43:19,981 --> 00:43:22,057
I see you're a born romantic.

479
00:43:23,860 --> 00:43:26,611
I see you've never known true love.

480
00:43:27,947 --> 00:43:30,520
I did. It shortened my leg.

481
00:43:32,034 --> 00:43:36,530
- I thought you fell off a horse.
- I did.

482
00:43:36,580 --> 00:43:39,071
I was in love with a trapeze artist.

483
00:43:39,124 --> 00:43:42,411
I should have known.
They always drop you at the last minute.

484
00:43:42,462 --> 00:43:45,167
He dropped me just before my act.

485
00:43:47,258 --> 00:43:50,876
It floored me. And the horse.

486
00:43:50,928 --> 00:43:53,965
With me under it.

487
00:43:55,892 --> 00:43:58,264
The mauresque?

488
00:43:58,311 --> 00:44:01,228
Still, true love does exist.

489
00:44:01,272 --> 00:44:05,222
I'm not saying it doesn't.
After 30 years behind this bar,

490
00:44:05,277 --> 00:44:08,941
I'm an expert. I can even give you the recipe.

491
00:44:11,282 --> 00:44:14,034
Take two regulars.

492
00:44:14,077 --> 00:44:17,362
Let each think the other fancies them.
Leave it to simmer.

493
00:44:17,413 --> 00:44:19,322
It never fails.

494
00:44:28,258 --> 00:44:29,456
Excuse me!

495
00:44:29,509 --> 00:44:31,252
Excuse me.

496
00:44:31,302 --> 00:44:33,094
- I've had enough.
- I'll go.

497
00:44:36,766 --> 00:44:38,842
Haven't you hurt enough people?

498
00:44:42,647 --> 00:44:44,307
Gina can defend herself.

499
00:44:44,357 --> 00:44:47,607
I don't mean Gina. I mean Georgette.

500
00:44:50,822 --> 00:44:51,853
Georgette?

501
00:44:51,906 --> 00:44:54,991
Open your eyes! She craves your attention

502
00:44:55,034 --> 00:44:56,826
but you only have eyes for Gina.

503
00:44:59,080 --> 00:45:02,413
Poor girl! The things she does

504
00:45:02,458 --> 00:45:04,534
to catch your eye!

505
00:45:07,088 --> 00:45:09,164
You really must be blind.

506
00:45:17,849 --> 00:45:19,925
I'm off on a date. Bye!

507
00:45:19,976 --> 00:45:22,052
Goodbye.

508
00:45:24,355 --> 00:45:26,727
Whoever her new one is,

509
00:45:26,774 --> 00:45:30,357
he can't be worse
than that nut with his tape recorder.

510
00:45:31,570 --> 00:45:33,481
Joseph's not so nutty.

511
00:45:34,533 --> 00:45:36,276
